body:
Example playground: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=680b2c1586e6eee26bdb90717fd37a07

Currently, the following piece of code:

```rust
#![allow(unused_variables)]

use std::fs::File;
use std::io;


fn main() -> Result<(), io::Error> {
    let file = File::create("hello.txt").unwrap();
    write_to_file(file, String::from("Hello File!"));
    write_to_file(file, String::from("Hello File!"));
    Ok(())
}

fn write_to_file(file: File, string_buffer: String) -> Result<usize, io::Error> {
    unimplemented!()
}
```

Leads to the following Diagnostics:

```rust
 
Standard Error

   Compiling playground v0.0.1 (/playground)
error[E0382]: use of moved value: `file`
  --> src/main.rs:10:19
   |
8  |     let file = File::create("hello.txt").unwrap();
   |         ---- move occurs because `file` has type `File`, which does not implement the `Copy` trait
9  |     write_to_file(file, String::from("Hello File!"));
   |                   ---- value moved here
10 |     write_to_file(file, String::from("Hello File!"));
   |                   ^^^^ value used here after move
```

This error message is frequently one of the first that new user of Rust (also in my trainings) see, and it leads to multiple confusions: a) what is a "move" (when learning about Ownership) and b) what is the `Copy` trait and how do I implement it?.

It does not give helpful advice (e.g. explaining that the value is gone because Ownership was given away). In cases where the value is `Clone`, no recommendation to clone is given ([example](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=680b2c1586e6eee26bdb90717fd37a07)). In cases where the value is indeed POD and in control of the user, we could also give a recommendation to derive `Copy`.

